<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-08-21T14:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-08-21T14:00:00-05:00" n="322" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d322">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">838.00/3239: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Armour</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Port-au-Prince</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-08-21T14:00:00-05:00">August 21, 1934—2
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 2:30 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>91. Department’s telegram of August 14, 1 p.m.<note n="24" xml:id="d322fn24">Not printed, but see instruction No. 206, August
                                14, 1934, to the Minister in Haiti, <ref target="#pg_306">p.
                                    306</ref>.</note> Ceremonies this morning passed off very
                            satisfactorily. I read President Roosevelt’s letter at the Palace to
                            which President Vincent replied in similar spirit.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Armour</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>